Part B: Password Security Review

What makes a strong password?
A strong password is long, unique, and difficult to guess.
It should contain a combination of uppercase letters, lowercase letters, numbers, and special characters. 
Strong passwords reduce the risk of unauthorized access to accounts.

Why should passwords be unique?
Passwords should be unique because if one account gets compromised, attackers cannot use the same password to access other accounts.
Unique passwords help limit the impact of a security breach.

What is Multi-Factor Authentication (MFA)?
Multi-Factor Authentication (MFA) is a security method that requires users to verify their identity using two or more factors,
such as a password and a one-time code sent to a phone or email. MFA provides an additional layer of security.

What are the risks of password reuse?
Password reuse increases security risks because if one website suffers a data breach, attackers can use the stolen password to access other
accounts belonging to the same user. This can lead to identity theft, financial loss, and loss of personal information.

Password Policy

• Passwords must be at least 12 characters long.
• Passwords should contain both uppercase and lowercase letters.
• Passwords must include at least one number.
• Passwords should contain special characters such as @, #, $, %, etc.
• Personal information such as names, birthdays, and phone numbers should not be used.
• A unique password should be used for each account.
• Multi-Factor Authentication (MFA) should be enabled whenever possible.
• Passwords should not be shared with anyone.
• Passwords should be stored securely using a password manager.
• Passwords should be changed immediately if a compromise is suspected.
